Thread on my favourite and most curious unorthodox/puzzle chess pieces.

Figures that are not normally used in regular games, but are often seen in chess problems.

This is more interesting than it sounds, I promise.

1. Nightrider (also known as the "Knightmare")

Unlike a regular Knight, the Nightrider is able to move an INFINITE number of steps in the same direction.

2. Camel

Another "leaper"-style piece that resembles the Knight is the Camel.

It acts like an elongated Knight.

I very much enjoy the lore behind it - desert camels, being evolved for travels with longer durations, also being able to move a longer distance on the board.
HNNNNNNNNG

3. Mann

A King without his crown and throne - a common man, who, unlike the simple Pawn, can move in all directions like a king.

A man with royal blood, denied his destiny, and reduced to a common mass of meat in the battlefield. Perhaps the most tragic chess piece of them all!

4. Amazon

If we disallow ourselves to be too creative, this should be the strongest chess piece possible.

It is the sum of all other orthodox figures - combining the dominion of the queen with the Knight's ability to leap: a proud Queen of the wild, riding her steed into battle
well u need to regulate ur sleep !
I would enjoy seeing Hollywood itself remade into 2d, if you know what I mean
More like "turned into 2d" if we have to use correct terminology

5. Anti-King

In check when not threatened. If, when in check, he's unable to move to position, in which he is able to be attacked, the player loses.

A maddened royal, seeking destruction and ruin. The story of King Saul quietly echoes in the figure of the Anti-King. Saddening!
Could 100% get that Captains of Crush certification

6. Archbishop

Superior to the simple Bishop, the Archbishop is allowed to once per turn "bounce" from any edge of the board.

In some versions, more than one "bounce" is allowed, making for some absolutely unexpected plays.

I'll let y'all figure out the lore yourselves.

7. Bishight

A rare piece that moves forwards as a Bishop, and backwards as a Knight.

Able to infiltrate the enemies and quickly outmaneuver them, this is a figure with a high skill ceiling.

A fearful Bishop that is quick to panic in battle - a marauder posing as a holy man?
I was the one asking! And no, he sadly was not

8. Blind Tiger

A novelty piece, that moves one square like a king, but is unable to move orthogonally forwards.

It is known, and said even in the Bible, that the tiger's most dangerous weapon are his sharp eyes. A tiger without his vision is castrated, impotent. See the irony?

The only criteria by which we can compare different civilizations and eras is the number of tiger paintings produced.

A better peoples would fill entire galleries with tiger imagery of all sorts every night!

I installed an app on my phone called "Quizzar" that made me answer questions every morning and in return gave me a few cents. At first it asked me stuff like "Do you own a gaming console" and "What is your favourite cereal brand", stuff that is useful for ads/marketing research

then one day it asked me "Have you ever been bitten by a snake?" I said "no" and now every day it asks me the same question "And would you like to be?". I keep sayin no but im startin to get curious what will happen if one day I chose the "yes" option. been thinkin bout it a lot.
